    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Actually, thinking about this more, it's not about implicit vs explicit.  It's about how the code reacts if `Authorize()` returns an _unexpected_ error.  By only handling the context case, we'd be the in the same boat again of swallowing the unexpected error and treating it like an unauthorized response.\r\n\r\nIf we instead handle the _expected_ errors, and return any others, we're less likely to incorrectly ignore them.",
    "commit_id": "75b840aab57362b30d9bac7b1c672f9b010daba7",
    "created_at": "2023-04-13T17:41:44Z",
    "diff_hunk": "@@ -137,6 +137,9 @@ func Filter[O Objecter](ctx context.Context, auth Authorizer, subject Subject, a\n \t\t\terr := auth.Authorize(ctx, subject, action, o.RBACObject())\n \t\t\tif err == nil {\n \t\t\t\tfiltered = append(filtered, o)\n+\t\t\t} else if ctx.Err() != nil {\n+\t\t\t\t// Exit early if the error comes from the context\n+\t\t\t\treturn nil, ctx.Err()",
    "html_url": "https://github.com/coder/coder/pull/7119#discussion_r1165845331",
